s parents did not speak good English, and in Prague German was still the language of the middle-classes, a reflection of the Hapsburg Empire.  Czechoslovakia, as it was then called, was part of the Hapsburg Empire, so they moved to Prague, and my \'85
 after the German Invasion, my mother managed to get sponsorship in the UK, through a Quaker Organisation in the UK, in England, so she left at the age of 18, in 1938, and came to England, and began life as a domestic to a pharmacist in So
uthampton.  My father was born and brought up in Czechoslovakia, in Bohemia.  His father was a businessman, he had a textile agency in a small town, which was a textile town, and my father was the youngest of three brothers, the eldest of the three was 
\'85 academically the most gifted, and he went to university, the Charles University in Prague, where he studied chemistry, and he specialised in the chemistry of dyestuffs, and through a contact that my father\rquote s father had, my father\rquote 
s eldest brother left for Manchester in 1936, because textiles and dyeing was, you know, an important part of the economy of Manchester, and he got a job in a dyestuffs factory in Manchester.  And because my father\rquote 
s eldest brother was already in England in 1936, so my uncle \endash  my father\rquote s eldest brother \endash 
 could arrange for his two younger brothers to come out, which they did, although they came out very late.  My father arrived in England on August 30}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\super\insrsid3175624\charrsid6253416 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f42\fs22\insrsid3175624\charrsid6253416 , 1939, so he cut it quite close!  He cut it quite fine!  And he settled in Manchester.  He met my mother at a Refugee Club in Manchester - because by then my mother had moved to Manchester 
